<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-548-732  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 548 732.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Design  May 24 1990 v38 n10 p65(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Evaluate complex systems with self-test. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cameron, Robin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Efficient evaluation of an ASCII-based system can be done withself-test modules.andP;  Self-test is applicable because manuallyoperated test systems are too slow and too prone to human error.andO;Test engineers and design engineers must work together closely todevelop an efficient self-test module.andP;  Choosing the correctmeasurement circuitry is important.andP;  The first step is analyzing asystem's testing requirements.andP;  This enables the engineers todivide the system into cleanly partitioned modules for efficienttesting.andP;  Next, each module is evaluated individually to determinethe hardware and software needed for proper testing procedures.andO;Engineers should also analyze the resulting modules to determinewhere they are to be used in the product cycle and what interfaceis needed.andP;  Usually one or more of three modes is needed: burn-in,which is self-looping and does not require a user interface;bench-test, which needs a command line, menu, or windowed userinterface and an external display and keyboard devices; andcomputerized automated test, which needs a computer commandinterface, computer error responses, and data logging.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TestingSelf-Test CapabilityBurn-In TestingComputerized Testing.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   An external self-test module. (chart)DC verifier circuit. (chart)High-speed sampling circuit. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>